description: From Middle English wynde, probably from wynden (“to wind, proceed, go”). Compare also Old English ġewind; Old Norse venda.

entries.meaning: (chiefly Scotland, Northumbria) A narrow lane, alley or path, especially one between houses.
examples: He flew through the moonlight streets, clattering over cobbles, darting down narrow alleys and up twisty wynds, racing to his love.
